public abstract class TestCase
extends Asserts

This class provides the base framework to write a unit test. Simply extend this class and provide an implementation for runTest().

In general, collections of TestCases can be placed in a TestSuite which is a subclass of TestCase in accordance with the Composite design pattern.

A spin on a straight unit test is the concept of "test sets". A particular TestCase may not be suitable for all environments. For example, a test may only be intended to run on the Dallas Semiconductor's TINI board, or a comms test may require a certain test set up. In that case, the TestCase may be declared to belong to one or more "test sets", using addTestSet(java.lang.String). By default, a TestCase belongs to all test sets. The null test set includes all TestCases.

testSetsSupported

private boolean testSetsSupported(java.lang.String[] targetTestSets)
This function determines whether the TestCase belongs to this testSet.
Parameters:
testSet - The testSet that the TestCase may (or may not) belong to.
Returns:
If testSets is null (ie the TestCase belongs to all testSets), or testSet is "" (ie the testSet is the null case) or the TestCase supports the specified testSet then true. Otherwise false.

addTestSet

public void addTestSet(java.lang.String testSet)
This command adds the specified testSet to the list of testSets supported by this TestCase. If this method is not called for a TestCase, then the TestCase belongs to all testSets.

go

public void go(java.lang.String[] targetTestSets,
               TestReport report)
This method executes the test, provided it belongs to one of the specified testSets.
Parameters:
testSet - The test will only be executed if it belongs to this testSet (or it belongs to all testSets). If testSet is the empty string then the TestCase will execute.

freeMemory

protected void freeMemory()
This utility method can be called by any test to ensure it has enough headroom on the TINI. In theory, it should pause long enough for any rubbish to be garbage collected.
